045–1102","2 October 1102":"2 October 1102","1110":"1110","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1135":"1135","1102":"1102","1079":"1079","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1045":"1045","1166":"1166","1100":"1100","1 February 1120":"1 February 1120","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fossard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fozard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fozard","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Old French personal name  <i>Fossard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":7,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Bo